WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.880
So now that we have Python and VS Code set up, the next thing that we have to do is set

2
00:00:03.880 --> 00:00:05.720
up our virtual environment.

3
00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:08.960
Before we do that, we have to actually talk about what our virtual environments and what

4
00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:11.400
problems do they try to address.

5
00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:15.140
So let me give you a little bit of an example scenario of the issue that we can run into

6
00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:19.660
when working with specific packages within Python on your local machine.

7
00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:23.200
So let's say that we created a project and this project is called project one.

8
00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:27.559
And what we need to do is we need to install FastAPI version 1.2.1.

9
00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:28.559
So what do we do?

10
00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:32.080
We need to install version 1.2.1 on our machine so that we can actually

11
00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:33.080
use that version.

12
00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:38.160
Now, let's say later down the road, we start a new project called project two.

13
00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:43.020
And let's say this version requires us to run FastAPI version 2.4.3

14
00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:45.360
because we want to try out some of the newer features.

15
00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:50.320
Well, at this point, if we need to try out a newer version, we have to upgrade FastAPI

16
00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:53.380
to version 2.4.3 on our local machine.

17
00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:57.660
And this may or may not be a problem, it really just depends on if version 2.4.3 is backwards compatible with version 1.2.1.

18
00:00:57.660 --> 00:01:02.400

19
00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:05.919
Because if version 2.4.3 has breaking changes, then ultimately, that's

20
00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:09.419
going to create issues with our project one because that project expects us to run version

21
00:01:09.419 --> 00:01:10.919
1.2.1.

22
00:01:10.919 --> 00:01:14.699
And so if we can upgrade, well, we're in a little bit of a pickle because one project

23
00:01:14.699 --> 00:01:18.199
needs one version, the other project needs another version, we can have two different

24
00:01:18.199 --> 00:01:20.160
versions installed on our machine.

25
00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:21.760
So what exactly do we do?

26
00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:25.059
Well, this is where virtual environments come into play.

27
00:01:25.059 --> 00:01:28.699
So with virtual environments, let's say we want to create a project.

28
00:01:28.699 --> 00:01:32.019
So we create project one, and what we do is we create a virtual environment, call it whatever

29
00:01:32.019 --> 00:01:33.019
you want.

30
00:01:33.019 --> 00:01:37.620
And so this is an isolated environment that will not affect any other environments.

31
00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:41.379
And within this environment, we can install any Python packages, running whatever version

32
00:01:41.379 --> 00:01:45.300
we want, and it's completely isolated to this project.

33
00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:49.059
And so when we create a second project, what we can do is we can create its very own virtual

34
00:01:49.059 --> 00:01:51.879
environment as well, we'll call it virtual environment two.

35
00:01:51.879 --> 00:01:56.199
And within this virtual environment, we can install any version of any package that we

36
00:01:56.199 --> 00:01:57.199
want.

37
00:01:57.199 --> 00:01:59.279
So then we can install version 2.4.3.

38
00:01:59.279 --> 00:02:03.480
And so both of these virtual environments are completely separated, completely isolated

39
00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:04.559
from one another.

40
00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:09.119
And so we can essentially install multiple different versions of a single package for

41
00:02:09.119 --> 00:02:10.419
each of our projects.

42
00:02:10.419 --> 00:02:14.839
And that way, our projects don't end up stepping on the toes of other projects.

43
00:02:14.839 --> 00:02:18.500
And so now that we have a basic understanding of virtual environments, let's go ahead and

44
00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:21.940
figure out how we can actually create our first virtual environment and use it within

45
00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:22.580
our project.
